The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro

 The City Diary

 A 22-year-old labourer named Ananta Rang was crushed to death under iron angles while unloading a consignment from a truck at the factory where he worked at Dasnagar, in Howrah, about 6.30am on Wednesday. Local residents demonstrated at the factory gate, demanding adequate compensation for the labourers family, and refused to hand over the body to police. The owner of the factory agreed to pay a compensation. The body was then sent for post-mortem. 

 Taxi driver Santosh Verma was arrested near Vivekananda Road on Wednesday afternoon while he was picking up a bundle of cash kept by the side of the street. A few currency notes were blown away by a breeze during the process, prompting pedestrians to alert a traffic sergeant, who arrested Verma. About Rs 4,500 was found on the cabbie and deposited at Girish Park police station. 

 Detective department sergeant Saswata Chakraborty was remanded in judicial custody for two weeks on Wednesday. He was arrested on Tuesday for allegedly torturing his wife Mitra. 

 Eastern Railway will run a Howrah-Ajmer special train via Asansol on July 14 for Urs Mela. The train will leave Howrah at 11pm on July 14 and reach Ajmer at 4.30am on July 16. The special train will consist of 15 coaches, including an AC three-tier coach.

 Subhas Mukherjee, 36, committed suicide by hanging himself in the kitchen of his house on Bhukailash Road, in the port area, on Wednesday. According to police, Mukherjee was unemployed and was suffering from acute depression since his fathers death in 2005.

 Susmita Mondal, an 18-year-old housewife, was found hanging in the bedroom of her Baruipur house on Wednesday morning. According to police, she had married Chattu six months back. The husband is absconding.

 National Institute of Cholera and Enteric Diseases will test the effectiveness of a Japanese health drink that claims to prevent diarrhoea. The drink will be served to around 4,800 children of the Topsia and Tiljala areas. 

